<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-155-088  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 155 088.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  Jan 1990 v24 n8 p42(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Office automation: opening the door on tomorrow.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wohl, Amy D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Office automation is being implemented slowly in businesses,making it appear to some that the revolution predicted neveroccurred.andP;  It occurred, or is occurring, in ways much differentthan the experts anticipated, particularly when looking at thetypical office desktop of 1990.andP;  There are approximately 35million microcomputers in use today, most of which are found inoffices, but most have slow processing speeds and only 640Kbytesof accessible memory; they also are unsuitable for the graphicallyoriented computing environments of the next decade and beyond.andO;Multiuser applications such as electronic mail can be implementedas software rather than as complete systems, which brings costsdown and encourages the acquisition of even more microcomputers to'complete' the office automation.andP;  The increased use of local areanetworks and new products expected from IBM, DEC and other vendorsare described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationMarket AnalysisIndustry AnalysisUser NeedsTrendsLocal Area NetworksCompetitionMicrocomputersOrganizational Behavior.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>